<subSubSection id="41A7E139A996AAEACEBA2A347523F58F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="5B5037DE2846A7F025D1E093C09AFB1C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="72BF521C5AC1F63505B6523EF008F25A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length male 8-10 mm, female 10-12 mm. 
<taxonomicName id="72ABFE2870B625764C564FBB6444274D" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon chrysopygus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chrysopygus">
<emphasis id="E86DF9DD2A6F0DB34EC5D01239135AC6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon chrysopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="72BE73321C9BA10BE72C9D61C638365B" lsidName="flavofascium" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavofascium">
<emphasis id="0664725BD89D07899C0B70908A24B9F6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">flavofascium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. Within this group, it is the only species in which the male has no yellow wing markings, the wing being entirely dusky grey. In the female there is a large yellow part in the wing basally, whereas cells r2+3 and r4+5 are entirely dark. The postponotum is pilose.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A8398D90479F592F9AB85BB46C2DEB32" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9A08DD51D96081BBE2D9EFFF06789585" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="28A5EF84D7E7FCFD29DF4D5122AEB6DD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Known from Belize, Costa Rica, El Salvador, and Mexico. This is the only known species of the 
<taxonomicName id="7A8B311313D333803A944F07B68C8E85" lsidName="flavofascium" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="flavofascium">
<emphasis id="2508BA05A87921EF7F9306B1D2ED1DDE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">flavofascium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group in Central America.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
